docs.abstract: Kyle Rittenhouse, accused of killing two people during protests of a police shooting, faces six criminal counts. His social media accounts showed strong support for officers.
docs.snippet: Kyle Rittenhouse, accused of killing two people during protests of a police shooting, faces six criminal counts. His social media accounts showed strong support for officers.
docs.lead_paragraph: He signed up to be a cadet in a program for teenagers who aspire to be police officers. He filled his Facebook page with support for Blue Lives Matter. He sat upfront at a rally for President Trump in January, and posted images of it on TikTok. And he chose to mark his 16th birthday by raising funds for a support group for the police called Humanizing the Badge.

headline.main: Suspect in Kenosha Killings Lionized the Police
headline.print_headline: Teen Suspect In Two Killings Lionized Police

docs.abstract: As a Black man and a public servant, I see that spectacle is drowning out the voices that need to be heard to make positive change.
docs.snippet: As a Black man and a public servant, I see that spectacle is drowning out the voices that need to be heard to make positive change.
docs.lead_paragraph: After the horrendous killing of George Floyd, people in Portland, Ore., joined with thousands across the country in demonstrations to address police reform and widespread systemic racism. The leaders of the Portland Police Bureau denounced this tragic death, and we reiterated our willingness to engage in reforms.

headline.main: I’m the Police Chief in Portland. Violence Isn’t the Answer.

docs.abstract: Wedding vendors are taking to social media to speak out on a host of social and political issues. Some risk losing followers, clients and money as a result. Others feel supported.
docs.snippet: Wedding vendors are taking to social media to speak out on a host of social and political issues. Some risk losing followers, clients and money as a result. Others feel supported.
docs.lead_paragraph: In June, the photographer Shakira Rochelle started taking photographs of Black Lives Matter protesters in her hometown Cincinnati. She shared the images and other supportive B.L.M. content on her personal Instagram account. Shortly, thereafter she received a text from a couple who had hired her to photograph their wedding.

headline.main: Some Wedding Vendors Face Fallout After Speaking Up on Social Issues
headline.print_headline: Speaking Up Possibly Means Losing the Job

docs.abstract: To a degree not seen before, players are kneeling for the United States national anthem and speaking out publicly on fighting racism, with backing from the National Hockey League.
docs.snippet: To a degree not seen before, players are kneeling for the United States national anthem and speaking out publicly on fighting racism, with backing from the National Hockey League.
docs.lead_paragraph: Minnesota Wild forward Matt Dumba walked to center ice before an N.H.L. game this month and addressed the television audience, not about the game but the need for the sport to fight racism.

headline.main: Hockey, Rocked by Racist Acts, Embraces Black Lives Matter Campaigns
headline.print_headline: Shaken by Racist Acts, Hockey Fights Back: ‘It’s Our Responsibility’

docs.abstract: New research shows that sign-ups may have surged in early June, boosting hopes that activists can turn energy in the streets into voter turnout this fall.
docs.snippet: New research shows that sign-ups may have surged in early June, boosting hopes that activists can turn energy in the streets into voter turnout this fall.
docs.lead_paragraph: In the nationwide protests after the killing of George Floyd in police custody, Democratic leaders held out hope that the sweeping calls for racial justice and structural change would have a decidedly conventional side effect: more people would be motivated to vote in the fall. Activists holding voter registration clipboards became commonplace at protests.

headline.main: Did the George Floyd Protests Boost Democratic Voter Registration?
headline.print_headline: Voter Registration Surged in June, Drawing on Enthusiasm Generated by Protests

docs.abstract: Carlos Delgado remembered the difficulty of demonstrating alone 16 years ago. Now, he and current players are encouraged by a growing sense of solidarity with Black athletes.
docs.snippet: Carlos Delgado remembered the difficulty of demonstrating alone 16 years ago. Now, he and current players are encouraged by a growing sense of solidarity with Black athletes.
docs.lead_paragraph: Carlos Delgado, the former Toronto Blue Jays and Mets slugger, was playing basketball with his 13-year-old son at their home in Puerto Rico on Wednesday evening when he noticed a news alert on his phone: The Milwaukee Bucks players were sitting out of their N.B.A. playoff game to protest systemic racism and police brutality following the shooting of Jacob Blake, a Black man, by police in Kenosha, Wis.

headline.main: After a Long Lull, Protesting Is Taking Hold Across Baseball
headline.print_headline: After a Long Lull, Protesting Becomes Popular Again in Baseball

docs.abstract: His family often asks me about Black Lives Matter and racism. My boyfriend is annoyed, but I’m happy to teach them.
docs.snippet: His family often asks me about Black Lives Matter and racism. My boyfriend is annoyed, but I’m happy to teach them.
docs.lead_paragraph: I am a young Black woman who’s been quarantining with my white boyfriend for months. It’s been mostly great for us as a couple. When we visit his family nearby, they often ask me about the Black Lives Matter protests, in which we’re participating. I find them genuinely interested, respectful and curious about why expressions like “All Lives Matter” are racist. I’m happy to engage. But my boyfriend gets furious with them! He turns simple questions into big fights. What am I missing?

headline.main: My Boyfriend Is Mad At His White Parents for Me. But I Don’t Care.

docs.abstract: Harry H. Rogers, who prosecutors say is an admitted K.K.K. leader, faces three additional counts of attempted malicious wounding, a felony.

docs.lead_paragraph: A man who prosecutors described as a Ku Klux Klan leader was sentenced this week to six years in prison after driving into a group of Black Lives Matter protesters outside Richmond, Va., in June.

headline.main: Virginia Man, Said to Be a Klan Leader, Gets 6 Years in Prison After Driving Into a Protest

docs.abstract: With colonialist statues being toppled in America and beyond, T asked five artists to envision a different kind of memorial, one that embodies this moment of reckoning.
docs.snippet: With colonialist statues being toppled in America and beyond, T asked five artists to envision a different kind of memorial, one that embodies this moment of reckoning.
docs.lead_paragraph: ACCORDING TO DATA compiled by the Southern Poverty Law Center, some 100 monuments to Confederate generals and politicians have been removed from American public land since June 2015, when Dylann Roof, a then 21-year-old white supremacist, murdered nine Black parishioners in a mass shooting at the Emanuel African Methodist Episcopal Church in Charleston, S.C., in a state that, at the time, still flew the Confederate flag over its capitol. More than a third of these monuments have been removed since May 25 of this year alone, when a Minnesota police officer named Derek Chauvin, who has been charged with second-degree murder, was caught on video kneeling on the neck of George Floyd, an unarmed Black man, for more than eight minutes while Floyd pleaded for his life. (As a point of comparison, for the nearly 100 years between 1923 and 2015, only nine such monuments were removed.)

headline.main: America’s Monuments, Reimagined for a More Just Future
